Lam Laam, Jaffa (b. 1973)<br>
<br>
Lam Laam, Jaffa received her BFA, MFA and Postgraduate Diploma in Education at the Chinese University of Hong Kong. She is now teaching at the Hong Kong Art School as Senior Lecturer and Programme Coordinator of Higher Diploma in Fine Art. <br>
<br>
She is a sculptor specializing in large-scale site-specific works of mixed-media sculptures and installations, which are mainly made with recycled materials like crate wood, old furniture and recycled umbrella fabric. In recent years, she has been involved in many public art and community projects in Hong Kong and overseas. Her works often explore issues related to local culture, history, the society and current affairs. <br>
<br>
Apart from solo exhibitions, Lam was invited to take part in many local and international exhibitions, as well as artist residency programmes in Kenya, Taiwan, Bangladesh, China, United States and Canada, etc. She was awarded Asian Cultural Council&rsquo;s Desiree and Hans Michael Jebsen Fellowship as recognition in 2006. <br>
<br>
The community project she started in Hong Kong in 2009 is titled &ldquo;Micro Economy&rdquo;, which acquired the exhibition presented by Hong Kong Arts Centre: Jaffa Lam Laam Collaborative: Weaver. This project was also exhibited in Japan&rsquo;s Setouchi Triennale 2013 representing Hong Kong. <br>
<br>
